erkley, to her efforts to fight against climate change and minimize environmental degradation. The letters act as snapshots, giving us glimpses of the lives and issues that dominated culture at the time of their writing. Among the many issues that the correspondence in Laura Nader explores are how a man on death row sees things, how scientists are concerned about and approach their subject matter, and how an anthropologist ponders issues of American survival. The result is an intriguing and comprehensive history of energy, physics, law, anthropology, feminism and legal anthropology in the United States, as well as a reflection of a lifelong career in legal scholarship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aAnthropologistszUnited States. 0aAnthropologyxHistoryy20th century. 0aAnthropologyxHistoryy21st century. 0aAnthropologyxPhilosophy. 4aAnthropology. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aWomens Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aLaura Nader, letters, feminism,.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2020z978311069046008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501752254zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501752254423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501752254.jpg  a978-3-11-069046-0  COR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2020b2020  a978-3-11-070471-